The Federal Government has been advised to seek the opinion of Nigerians on the planned removal of fuel subsidy. The Coordinator of Christ Apostolic Church, Babalola Memorial International Miracle Camp, Ikeji, Osun State, Prophet Sam Olu Alo said such would help the government in making decisions acceptable to the people. Alo urged Nigerians to love one another, fear God and continue to see the project Nigeria as theirs. The cleric said the decision to be paying N5,000 to some category of people after subsidy removal may not work.   ‘Improve budget allocation for education’     Challenges of operating business x-rayed     Islamic City petitions Buhari over ejection plans   Prophet Alo, who is planter of the Christ Apostolic Church (CAC) Grace of Mercy Prayer Mountain Adamimogo Outreach, said “There is no sin in the removal of fuel subsidy. But I heard they had resolved to be giving N5,000 stipend to the people. They need to come to the round table with the people to discuss better things to spend the money on that will be of benefit to all. - Advertisement - “There must be a dialogue on whether the removed subsidy should be used for construction of train tracks connecting all states of the federation so that farmers and business owners will benefit and employment will be created for youth. It could also be used for security, roads construction and electricity. “It must be attached to a particular project and backed by law, so that, it will be used for the purpose it is meant for”. Alo noted that fuel is also costly in most of the developed or less developed countries he had visited, but people there are not complaining because they see good roads, jobs, water, electricity provided by the government with their money. “If this is happening in Nigeria, people will not resist the move to remove the fuel subsidy”.